{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17534476","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17534476"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:46:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:46:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14980"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14980","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14980"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.43,0.44,0.07,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7668"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60386"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7668","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7668"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14980"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45811"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"33"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"104"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4608"},{"type":"tags","id":"9217"},{"type":"tags","id":"12917"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18747"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39727"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60386","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/60386"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man is in the Intensive Care Unit (ICU)following coronary artery bypass grafting three days ago. The junior doctor in the ICU is asked to review the patient for worsening shortness of breath and hypotension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell and distressed. His pulse rate is 120/min and regular on cardiac monitoring, invasive blood pressure 85/60 mmHg on a radial arterial line, respiratory rate 28/min, SpO2 94% on 6 L/min oxygen via nasal cannula, and temperature 37.5\u00b0C. The central venous pressure (CVP) reading on his internal jugular central line is reading at 21mmHg (normal 0-12). It is also noted on his arterial line trace that his blood pressure drops by 15 mmHg during inspiration. He has cool peripheries with delayed capillary refill time. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely type of shock present in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Neurogenic shock","Obstructive shock","Cardiogenic shock","Hypovolaemic shock","Distributive shock"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features highly suggestive of cardiac tamponade causing obstructive shock. The clinical findings of elevated central venous pressure (CVP) and hypotension constitute two components of Beck\u0027s triad (the third being muffled heart sounds). The presence of pulsus paradoxus (a drop in systolic blood pressure \u0026gt;10 mmHg during inspiration) further supports this diagnosis. The recent cardiac surgery puts this patient at high risk for post-operative bleeding into the pericardial space.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObstructive shock\u003C/strong\u003E occurs when there is a mechanical impediment to cardiac filling or outflow. Common causes include cardiac tamponade, tension pneumothorax, and massive pulmonary embolism. The characteristic findings are hypotension with evidence of right heart strain (elevated CVP or JVP).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypovolaemic shock\u003C/strong\u003E would present with low jugular venous pressure and would be unlikely to cause pulsus paradoxus of this magnitude. While post-operative bleeding is common, the elevated CVP makes pure hypovolaemia unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECardiogenic shock\u003C/strong\u003E due to pump failure can occur after cardiac surgery but typically presents with hypotension and signs of pulmonary oedema and would not cause such prominent pulsus paradoxus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDistributive shock\u003C/strong\u003E, such as septic shock, is characterised by vasodilation leading to warm peripheries initially, unlike this patient\u0027s cool extremities. The elevated CVP would be unusual.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeurogenic shock\u003C/strong\u003E occurs after spinal cord injury and presents with bradycardia and warm peripheries due to loss of sympathetic tone, neither of which are present here.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Obstructive shock presents with hypotension, elevated central venous pressure, and muffled heart sounds in cardiac tamponade","Pulsus paradoxus \u003E10 mmHg is an important clinical sign of cardiac tamponade"],"references":["Haseer Koya H, Paul M. Shock. [Updated 2023 Jul 24]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK531492/","Teirney, P. Ahmed, B. Nichol, A. Shock: causes, initial assessment and investigations. Anaesthesia \u0026 Intensive Care Medicine, 2017, Volume 18, Issue 3, ISSN 1472-0299, https://doi.org/10.1016/j.mpaic.2016.12.003."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45811"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14980"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45811","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/45811"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-12T10:36:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-25T17:36:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7668"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60386"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"26","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/26"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd7c","name":"Critical Care Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"33","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/33"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiothoracic Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level III","synonyms":null,"description":"Apply, analyze, evaluate, and create (implementing, organizing, and critiquing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"104","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/104"},